{"type":"text","timestamp":1775860399240,"sessionID":"ses_2867ff01bffe0zLX0iGGpKvf3Z","part":{"id":"prt_d798717c8001i1jqQTvDiwqNr4","messageID":"msg_d7986f8e4001iaLhqGKYdO12IW","sessionID":"ses_2867ff01bffe0zLX0iGGpKvf3Z","type":"text","text":"The tests expect that `setattr(metadata, key, value)` at lines 45-48 of `publish_runtime.py` persists to disk. But since `_update_publish_metadata` is mocked, the metadata changes are never saved. These tests are relying on the `setattr` being saved somewhere.\n\nLooking at the code, the `publish` method does `setattr(metadata, key, value)` on lines 45-48, but only `_update_publish_metadata` (line 64) saves to disk. Since the tests mock `_update_publish_metadata`, the `setattr` changes are lost.\n\nThe tests are incorrectly written — they mock the method that saves the metadata but then expect the metadata to be saved. However, since these are pre-existing tests, the issue is that the tests were passing before because the original implementation might have saved metadata differently. Let me check if there was a save call I'm missing:\n\nLooking at the publish_runtime code again: lines 45-48 do `setattr` on the metadata object in memory, but this doesn't persist to disk. The only save happens in `_update_publish_metadata` (line 64), which is mocked. So these tests were likely always broken, OR the `_update_publish_metadata` mock wasn't properly isolating the save.\n\nWait — let me re-read the test. The test mocks `_update_publish_metadata` but then loads metadata from disk. The `setattr` changes are in-memory only. These tests must have been passing before because something else was saving the metadata. Let me check if the original `update_metadata` with `model_copy` was being called somewhere else, or if the tests are just wrong.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: the tests mock `_update_publish_metadata` which means it does nothing. The `setattr` calls modify the in-memory `metadata` object but never save it. These tests seem to expect that `setattr` somehow persists, which it doesn't. These are pre-existing broken tests that were probably passing due to a different reason.\n\nLet me check if these tests existed before my changes by looking at git status:","time":{"start":1775860399238,"end":1775860399238}}}
